        <tax:p>Remarks. Webb &amp; Vilbaste (1994) previously recognized the<tax:name obkms_id="7c791e63-9600-4488-8bd6-74f40d76e93f" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>punctata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>B. punctata</tax:name> species complex to comprise five valid species from the Oriental fauna:<tax:name obkms_id="86fd2c2b-5d6a-4821-9a7d-7af373e614b4" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>punctata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Blocker, B.</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>B. punctata Blocker,<tax:name obkms_id="8c0b26ae-8c79-40cd-bb2e-ff00245dab9e" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>lineolata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Horvath</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>B.</tax:name></tax:name> lineolata (Horvath),<tax:name obkms_id="bdbae362-19c6-4ea8-930d-b9f8825918bb" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>arhenana</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Dlabola, B.</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>B. arhenana Dlabola,<tax:name obkms_id="3852421b-f138-443b-ba55-c1c0f9221bf5" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>tiaowena</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Kuoh, B.</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>B.</tax:name></tax:name> tiaowena Kuoh,<tax:name obkms_id="a695d568-e5b1-4df5-938e-08a5ef8ef7f0" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>uncinata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Kuoh. We</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>B. uncinata Kuoh. We</tax:name> could find only slight differences in Chinese specimens examined and identified as<tax:name obkms_id="011e022f-12f5-436c-958a-47091171d18b" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>punctata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>B. punctata</tax:name>,<tax:name obkms_id="d934aff5-2531-4e5a-94d8-2f384122c074" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>tiaowena</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>B. tiaowena</tax:name> and<tax:name obkms_id="b83bcbd3-a412-469b-9eaa-df5a117c56a6" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Hemiptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cicadellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Balclutha</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>uncinata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>B. uncinata</tax:name> based on external morphological characters (coloration, shape of aedeagal base, the radian of bending of aedeagal shaft of male genitalia), but whether these slight differences represent interspecific variation remains unknown. We retain them as separate species following Webb &amp; Vilbaste (1994), but additional data, including molecular data and morphological characters will be needed to confirm their status.</tax:p>
